
   Latest News   10.4.90   

After a long exchange with NatNet, it
became clear that their new network will
not be adequate to Compunet's needs.

Meanwhile, Dialcom (the people who run
Prestel, Micronet & BT Gold) have been
in touch with us again.

They first contacted us last summer long
before Istel pulled the plug. We had
long nagotiations with them but we were
never happy with certain aspects. Now
that we have the agreement with Fastrak
where they are to help us set up on a
new network, we have a much better
footing on which to start new
negotiations.

The advantages of being part of Dialcom
include having a tried and tested and
very reliable telephone network, there
is at least one node in every area of
the UK. The list of nodes is very large!
Many areas have two or three nodes.

Among the disadvantages will be the
possibility of an increase in Subs
though we doubt this will be much and
with Fastrak's agreement, it may not
cost you (the user) anything extra at
all though this will have have to be
negotiated a long with everything else.

I personally would like to see us on the
Dialcom network, it has been around a
long time, it is the most reliable and
can support all baud rates. Nodes are
never down for long as Prestel is their
own system which (unlike Istel) gives
them very good reason to get the      
screwdrivers out very quickly!

There will not be any question of them
taking over Compunet and turning it into
another Prestel, this will be a major
part of the agreement. Compunet must
remain a 'users network' and not a
'subscribers database'.

We will give you news of our talks with
Dialcom whenever possible.

Mind you, the way things have been going
it would be no surprise if tomorrow I
had to tell you the talks were off!

BT (who'm Dialcom are a part of) said
they may be able to instal our direct
lines tomorrow (3 weeks early), here's
hoping we might be back on long distance
at least) very shortly.

